Student group promotes action

By Kathleen Scanlon
For The Pitt News

If members of the newly formed student group
Global Community Action can inspire one student
to write a letter to Congress, sophomore Hdeel
Abdelhady said her “head will be so big, they’ll
have to widen the sidewalks on campus.”

Abdelhady and graduate student Jennifer Nagel
formed Global Community Action this summer to
educate students about global issues and to
encourage students “to act on their knowledge.”

“We’re not the so-and-so group, we’re the action
group,” Abdelhady said. “I want to see some peo-
ple taking some initiative.”

The six members of Global Community Action,
in collaboration with Bosnian students at La
Roche College, have collected over 500 signatures
on a petition asking the United States to lift the
arms embargo on Bosnia. Two or three members
of the group will take the petition to Washington,
D.C. in July and meet with Sen. Bob Dole and a
Democratic senator.

Global Community Action wants the United
States to rally support from the European nations
for stronger international action in Bosnia,
Abdelhady said.

“With pressure, someone’s going to have to
act.”

Global Community Action wants to spur Pitt
students to apply some of that pressure on U.S.
leaders. The group will sponsor a presentation this
fall which will allow students to hear Bosnian
refugees describe life in a war zone, Abdelhady
said. The presentation will depict an accurate por-
trait of the devastation in Bosnia, she said, which
the media often distorts.

“Instead of saying ‘genocide,’ [media] use the
phrase ‘ethnic cleansing.’” The phrase is easier to
digest, but the problems not easy to digest.”

The group wants to dispel myths that Abdelhady
says blind students to reality.

“[Students], see little sound bites on TV but
don’t really know what’s going on,” she said. “If
they do know anything, it’s probably misleading.”

According to Abdelhady, many students think
the war in Bosnia is a civil war. Abdelhady said it
is not a civil war, because Bosnia declared inde-
pendence and the world acknowledged the coun-
try’s sovereignty. The war is then an aggression of
one state (Serbia), toward another (Bosnia), she
said.

Members of the group have distributed fact
sheets describing the history of the war and recent
military movements in Bosnia.

Global Community Action will also discuss
activist approaches to the situation in Haiti and the

