Don '1‘ Forget Russia

June 6, 1944: Russian troops battled the Germans on the
Eastern Front, while the remaining Allied powers took advantage
of Germany’s weak spot and dealt the blow that would lead to
the eventual fall of Nazi Germany.

June 6, 1994: Soldiers of the United States, Britain and Canada
strolled the beaches of Normandy as veterans of the historic
invasion,_reminiscing on the battle they took part in.

While most veterans and the rest of the world commemorate
D—Day with speeches, a reenactment of the paratroopers’ drop,
and the usual pomp and fanfare that surrounds these commemo-
rations, one vital partner of the invasion stands unjustly ignored
—— Russia. ‘

A recent poll that was conducted in the United States, Britain,
Germany and France to mark the 50th anniversary of the Allied
landing revealed that 31 percent of Germans believed it was a
combination of the United States, Britain, and then Soviet Russia
that did the most damage to Nazi Germany.

The bloodshed of 20 million Russians stands as testimony to
the German recognition of the sacrifices, bravery and fortitude
that resulted in the depletion of the German army.

The rest of the world, however, has forgotten over the years
what Russia really meant to the Allied powers, specifically in
this case to the invasion of Normandy.

The nations involved in this event should have invited Russia’
to partake in the commemoration of D—Day. Without them there
would have been nothing to remember.

