Homelessness alarming

   

“There’s no place
like home...”
crooned the pig-
tailed heroine of
The Wizard of Oz.
Dorothy was right.
Whether you live
in a Kansas farm-
house or a shoe-

 

Columnist

box apartment in
Meredith South Oakland,
McClure shelter symbolizes

safety and comfort. Shelter is, in fact,
as important to humans as food and
water. Unfortunately, the numbers of
those without shelter in the United
States continues to escalate atan
alarming rate.

Why are there so many homeless?
Two years ago there were roughly 3
million homeless people. Now even a
rough estimate is difficult to obtain
because the numbers have exploded.
The rising numbers are fed by unem-
ployment, declining income (two fac-
tors college seniors should be aware
of), lack of affordable housing, family
breakups and the deinstitutionalization
of state mental facilities. In short, a
single reason for the expansion of the
shelterless population doesn’t exist.

If you broke down the numbers of
homeless into categories,_ who would
you expect to find most represented?
Drunk fortysomethings?

Yes, the traditional wino continues to
thrive alongside the crackhead in
American cities. I won’t argue with
that. But by far the largest portion of
the United States’ homeless population

is represented by another group: chil- .

dren.

The number of kids in homeless
families is expanding faster than any
of the other categories of the homeless:
faster than battered women, the unem-
ployed, ex-cons, runaways, the mental-
ly ill, the elderly and immigrants.

In 1991, the Child Welfare League
estimated that more than one million
U.S. children were living in urban and
rural homeless families. Not only is
this an unfortunate reality, it’s cause
for alarm. But before you brand a
bleeding heart on my hide, read on.

Let’s focus on the children solely in

terms of our wallets, shall we? If these
kids don’t have homes,va considerable
number of them aren’t going to school.
(Mom and Dad can't exactly afford a
car at the moment and just where is an
addressless child supposed to catch a
school bus?) Assuming such a child is
receiving schooling, where would
he/she do homework?

Kids in homeless families can and

_do slip through society without receiv-

ing an education. Someone else will
pay down the road, whether it’s in the
form of welfare support, hospital
billing, or in the worst cases, jail and
legal fees.

What is to be done? I encourage you
to get involved because homelessness
has grown to such an extent that it is
now everyone’s problem. If, however,
you are like me and suffer from a con-
science whose twinging is ignored
when it comes to giving away money,
think about the larger sums that will be
missing from your future paychecks to
finance the lives of the uneducated,
illiterate and dependent adults that
homeless kids could become.

If you can spare a few dollars, some
canned goods, or some of your time
now, you’ll save yourself from a larger
bill later on.

As for that guy who asks me for a
quarter every Tuesday and Thursday as
I attempt to nonchalantly breeze past
him, hoping he won’t ask me for
money again — I don’t know if he
legitimately needs help or not. For this
reason, I advocate volunteering at or
donating to local agencies whose
employees know better. '

So far, this is the way I’ve been able
to reconcile my conscience with my
ever-present paranoia of being ripped
off. D .

In Pittsburgh there are several orga-
nizations and agencies who welcome
help and they’re listed under Human
Services in the white pages.

If you’re one of the phone bookless,
here are some suggestions: The
Salvation Army, The Jubilee Soup
Kitchen or Whale’s Tale.

Meredith McClure is a Pitt graduate
student and a Pitt News columnist.

