Homlessness annoying

The college cam-
pus of Oakland has
its own panhandle,
however, it is geo-
graphically unlike
 that of Florida or
 Texas. Forbes

Avenue, a narrow

stretch of road run-

     

Columnist 

_ ning through the
Rlck _ _ University of
Cardinal‘ Pittsburgh, is the

lifeline to the street beggars (or pan-
handlers) in the greater Oakland area.
The campus hangouts fall directly on
this main drag. These student gather-
ing-places are made up of a group of
bars, eateries, and shops; ideal ambush
points for panhandlers to pray on pass-
ing students. They stand holding cups,
shouting, “Change please?” When
passing with hands in pockets, con-
science often brings out a shiny trophy
in it. Is it conscience that lets that cur-
rency go? The sight of a grown adult,
standing all too often in the cold, wear-
ing their entire wardrobe on their per-
son, must hit a nerve somewhere
inside. Stopping to give a coin and dig-
gin’ through a tight jean pocket both
slow the process just enough to notice
the anguish on a face, the holes in the
tennis shoes worn by the salted side-
walk and possibly the rolled newspaper
that more than likely will serve as the
evening’s bedding. To finally make eye
contact is like looking into two pieces
of coal, darkened by a tale or story.
There has to be a story! _

In this world we live in today, people
do not want to hear stories about starv-
ing Third World nations, poverty-
strickencommunities, the homeless, or
anything else that shows a side of
depression.

People’s lives are depressed enough
with bills, payments, unemployment
and pregnancies to concern themselves
with the problems that appear on the
evening news or out of the mouth of
some bum talking about how he didn’t
get a fair shake at life. As busy college
students hustling to and from the class-
room, do we really have time for this?
Do we have the money to fund these
people? No! Of course not. The last

thing that a summer commuter needs_

to hear on his or her way to class is,
“Little help?” Why should I stop and
dig around in my pockets for change
that I probably will need later on in the
day or week for parking, or maybe bus
fare. Upon ending a tiring day at the
office, why ‘do I need to contend with
this harassment? In essence, that is
what this comes down to, simple
harassment. Just because the guy at the
local 7—Eleven opened the door for me
doesn’t mean that he is entitled to my
money. Since when did 7-Elevens pick
up door men on the payroll? Maybe it
might be a little more profitable if pan-
handlers were to get a real job; hell,
they are doing the same amount of
work opening and closing doors any-
way.

’ Oakland is a dying community. If it
wasn’t for the college campus Oakland
would have been dead years ago. Is it a
wonder that the area has atrophied?
Just look at the businesses on Forbes
Avenue. The whole street looks like a
slum. Panhandlers have roosted out-
side every business on the avenue,
deterring would—be customers. Isn’t
this loitering a crime? Maybe it should
be. Who wants to wade through a sea
of vagrants to get a workout at Forbes
Fitness Center or even a Coke at the 7-
Eleven, knowing full well that when
you come out you will be hounded for
change? People often use the avoid-
ance tactic to not have to exchange
words with the panhandler. A person
will actually cross the street and walk
on the other side to avoid passing the
person.

Hard-working people should not
have to throw table scraps to dregs
hitching rides on the tailgate of society.

This country was founded on hard
work and determination and this action
of non-working America is a virus rob-
bing us of our historical tradition of
being a capitalist—built economy, an
economy in which Americans work
their way up the social ladder and see
the horizon of success from the top
rung.

