moments in the life of pianist
and eccentric Glenn Gould
(Colm Feore), the film dances
through a standard litany of the
development of a genius from
boyhood on, peppered with
documentary-like interviews in
which actors play Gould’s
family, friends and musician
colleagues.

So the lives of Glenn Gould
become filtered through this
collection of moments, framed
at the beginning and ending
with the subject wandering a
whitewashed, frozen landscape

in abject loneliness. Thirty Two
Short Films takes great pains
to paint Gould as a marginal
figure. He’s the first concert
pianist to shed the tuxedo in
favor of informal dress and
there’s even a few minutes on
his pill—popping ways, his love
for amphetamines and the like.

After these scenes, Gould
comes across as kind of a
candy—assed subversive, a bor-
ing genius whose innovations
reverberate only among a
small circle of folks. And
Gould is just the kind of char-
acter that haughty classical-
music circles might embrace
as a vaunted eccentric because
he poses little or no threat to
their middle—class sensibilities.

But whenever the film wan-
ders here there is always his
music. It's this single, undeni-
able element of his life that
comes through untainted. Most
of the film manages to allow
the man’s playing and compo-
sitions to be seen and heard in
a way that allows even the
unwashed to grasp at just why
Gould was considered such a
genius.

 
     

