First off, most of the songs are mid/up tempo
rock songs; there’s little variety. Second, the band
sounds like an ultra—s1ick Nashville act that proba-
bly backs up Lorie Morgan in their spare time.
Their sound must come from the new country tra-
dition. It shares the sterile, brittle, guitar tones, dull
